<tr>
<td colspan="3" class="boilerplate metadata" style="line-height:10pt; padding:0.5em;"><small><b>Note</b>: This page may contain <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA" title="Wikipedia:IPA">IPA</a> phonetic symbols in <a href="/wiki/Unicode" title="Unicode">Unicode</a>.</small></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Skolt Sami</b> <i>(<span class="Unicode">sääˊmǩiõll</span>)</i> is a <a href="/wiki/Uralic_languages" title="Uralic languages">Uralic</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sami_languages" title="Sami languages">Sami</a> <a href="/wiki/Language" title="Language">language</a> spoken by approximately 400 speakers in <a href="/wiki/Finland" title="Finland">Finland</a>, mainly in <a href="/wiki/Sevettij%C3%A4rvi" title="Sevettijärvi">Sevettijärvi</a>, and approximately 20–30 speakers of the Njuõˊttjäuˊrr (Notozero) dialect in an area surrounding <a href="/wiki/Lake_Lovozero" title="Lake Lovozero">Lake Lovozero</a> in <a href="/wiki/Russia" title="Russia">Russia</a>. Skolt Sami used to also be spoken on the <a href="/wiki/Neiden,_Finnmark" title="Neiden, Finnmark">Neiden</a> area of <a href="/wiki/Norway" title="Norway">Norway</a>, although it has died out there. It is written using a Roman <a href="/wiki/Orthography" title="Orthography">orthography</a> that was made official in 1973.</p>
